self to its broader symbolic ramifications, Klaver addresses questions as disparate as the social constructedness of the body, the perception and treatment of death under late capitalism, and the ubiquity of paranoia in contemporary culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAutopsyxHistory. 0aAutopsyxSocial aspects. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780791483428?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483428423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483428/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles